result.execSummary:
The defendant Mei Zhen Tan was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Resisting/Obstructing. This is not a criminal offense and results only in a money penalty for this offense.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Cash bail applied to fine. Fine paid in full.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Mei Zhen Tan in court.  Peter Michael Tempelis appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Jasmine Chan appears as interpreter, by zoom, and is sworn-in. 

Court advises of right to an attorney.

Ms. Tan states that she will be retaining an attorney. Defendant's friend/former landlord appears with her and makes statements. Court will set another date to give the Defendant time to obtain an Attorney.   Defendant to apply at Public Defender's Office for representation.

Attorney Cassie Miller from the Public Defender's Office now appears as friend of the Court. Atty Miller will go into a zoom breakout room to assist Defenadnt with intepreter. 

State moves to amend to a county ordinance 13.102(c)(7). Defense has no objection. Defendant enters a plea of no-contest to amended charge. Court finds the defendant guilty of the amended charge. 

Court order the following:
FINE: $267.50 to be paid within 90 days, alternate is entry of civil judgment.
To Seal Victim/Witness Identification Key, signed by Judge Brad D. Schimel on April 13th, 2022.

Defendant to comply with I.D. Processing.  Defendant is not to have any violent contact with victim A listed in the Criminal Complaint/Victim Identification Key.   Defendant is not to share, reproduce or distribute any personal and/or identifying information about the crime victim(s), except to their attorney.

01:59 PM Defendant Mei Zhen Tan in court, in custody, with attorney Ricardo Tapia, as a friend of the court.    District Attorney's Office Law Intern appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Cantonese interpreter Ken ID#251278 appearing by phone.  Defendant was not evaluated by the public defender's office, could not communicate with the defendant.    Defense acknowledges receipt of complaint and waives reading of complaint.  Service admitted/advised of charges and potential penalties.  NOT GUILTY PLEA ENTERED.  Hearing scheduled for May 19, 2022 at 10:30 am.
Waukesha County Public Safety Assessment Report filed by Wisconsin Community Services.
Victim/Witness Identification Key filed, under seal,  by the District Attorney's office.
